                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d633">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8926: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-10T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 10, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 10—3:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>344. My 327, March 7, 6 p.m., and 300, March 3, 5 p.m.<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d633fn44">Latter not printed.</note> From same reliable source I am
                    informed Mussolini is now in Albania and insists upon proceeding with
                    counter-offensive against Greeks. He is determined at least to begin without
                    assistance of Germans. I am also informed that offensive may be undertaken at
                    end of this week.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
